{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"e030c76e-e9a3-4e2e-a456-525283049b44","content":"The migration is straightforward. In your project file, either **remove** the `<UseVSTest>true</UseVSTest>` property or set it to `false`:\n\n```xml\n<Project Sdk=\"MSTest.Sdk/3.8.0\">\n  <PropertyGroup>\n    <!-- Remove or set to false: -->\n    <!-- <UseVSTest>true</UseVSTest> -->\n  </PropertyGroup>\n</Project>\n```\n\n**Key changes to be aware of:**\n\n1. **`<UseVSTest>true</UseVSTest>`** → remove it (Microsoft.Testing.Platform is the default in MSTest.Sdk).\n2. **Test runner CLI** changes — you run tests with `dotnet test` as before, but the underlying runner is now Microsoft.Testing.Platform instead of VSTest.\n3. **Command-line filters** — VSTest's `--filter` syntax is replaced with `--filter` using the new platform's syntax (mostly compatible, but check complex expressions).\n4. **`.runsettings`** — still supported, but some VSTest-specific adapter settings may not apply.\n5. **Extensions** — if you use VSTest-specific adapters/loggers (e.g., custom `ITestLogger`), you'll need their Microsoft.Testing.Platform equivalents (e.g., TRX report: add `<EnableMicrosoftTestingExtensionsCodeCoverage>` or `<OutputType>exe</OutputType>` isn't needed since MSTest.Sdk handles it).\n\n**TL;DR**: Just delete the `<UseVSTest>true</UseVSTest>` line — the SDK defaults to Microsoft.Testing.Platform. Then do a `dotnet test` to verify everything still passes.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"999f9bbd-41e1-404e-9d74-bc9cdbc19c5a","outputTokens":406,"requestId":"A03B:16E70A:BDE00D:DEC379:69FE866B"},"id":"619c626c-b433-4867-aa49-d957fa72581c","timestamp":"2026-05-09T00:57:26.708Z","parentId":"1784231a-70eb-4763-90ba-1ab1d1f27a12"}
